Core Components
CRDs
KubeSwift defines four primary Kubernetes resources.
SwiftGuest
Represents a running virtual machine.
Example:

apiVersion: swift.kubeswift.io/v1alpha1
kind: SwiftGuest
spec:
  imageRef:
    name: ubuntu-cloud
  guestClassRef:
    name: default
  seedProfileRef:
    name: minimal

Status contains:

phase
conditions
podRef
nodeName
network.primaryIP


SwiftImage
Represents a VM disk image.
Example:

spec:
  source:
    http:
      url: https://cloud-images.ubuntu.com/noble/current/noble-server-cloudimg-amd64.img
  format: qcow2

During import:

qcow2 → raw conversion

Runtime disks must be raw.

SwiftSeedProfile
Defines cloud-init configuration.
Used to inject:

user data
metadata
network config
SSH keys

Rendered as a NoCloud seed ISO.

SwiftGuestClass
Defines default runtime resources:

CPU
memory
storage defaults


Controller Architecture
Controllers are written in Go using controller-runtime.
Main controllers:

internal/controller/swiftguest
internal/controller/swiftimage


SwiftImage Controller
Handles image preparation.
Workflow:

SwiftImage created
      │
      ▼
Import Job created
      │
      ▼
Image downloaded
      │
      ▼
qemu-img convert qcow2 → raw
      │
      ▼
Artifact stored
      │
      ▼
status.phase = Ready


SwiftGuest Controller
Responsible for launching the VM.
Workflow:

SwiftGuest created
      │
      ▼
Resolve references
      │
      ▼
Generate runtime intent
      │
      ▼
Create launcher pod
      │
      ▼
Update status


Runtime Intent
Before launching a VM, the controller creates a runtime intent describing how the VM should run.
Example:

{
  "guestId": "default/sample",
  "cpu": 2,
  "memory": 2048,
  "rootDisk": {
      "path": "/var/lib/kubeswift/disks/root/image.raw"
  },
  "seedPath": "/var/lib/kubeswift/seed"
}

The runtime intent is mounted into the launcher container.

Launcher Pod
Each SwiftGuest runs inside a pod.

SwiftGuest Pod
 ├─ init container: network-init
 └─ launcher container: swiftletd


network-init
Prepares networking inside the pod.
Steps:

create bridge br0
create tap interface tap0
attach tap0 to bridge
start dnsmasq DHCP server

Example DHCP range:

10.244.x.x


swiftletd
swiftletd is the VM launcher written in Rust.
Responsibilities:

load runtime intent
prepare runtime directory
generate seed ISO
spawn Cloud Hypervisor
monitor VM lifecycle
discover guest IP
report status


Runtime Directory
Each VM gets a runtime directory.
Example:

/var/lib/kubeswift/run/default-sample

Contains:

ch.sock
serial.sock
seed/
seed.iso


Cloud Hypervisor Invocation
swiftletd launches Cloud Hypervisor with arguments similar to:

cloud-hypervisor \
  --api-socket path=/var/lib/kubeswift/run/default-sample/ch.sock \
  --memory size=2048M \
  --cpus boot=2 \
  --kernel /usr/share/kubeswift-firmware/hypervisor-fw \
  --disk path=/var/lib/kubeswift/disks/root/image.raw \
  --disk path=/var/lib/kubeswift/run/default-sample/seed.iso \
  --serial socket=/var/lib/kubeswift/run/default-sample/serial.sock \
  --console off \
  --net tap=tap0

Important:

root disk must be raw


Networking Model
Networking uses tap + bridge inside the pod.

Guest VM
   │
virtio-net
   │
tap0
   │
br0
   │
pod network

dnsmasq provides DHCP.
Example lease range:

10.244.125.10 → 10.244.125.20


IP Discovery
swiftletd monitors DHCP leases.
When a lease appears:

guest IP discovered

Then:

SwiftGuest.status.network.primaryIP updated

Example:

status:
  network:
    primaryIP: 10.244.125.12


Guest Lifecycle
SwiftGuest lifecycle:

Pending
   │
   ▼
Scheduled
   │
   ▼
Running
   │
   ▼
Stopped / Failed

Conditions include:

Resolved
PodScheduled
GuestRunning


Console Access
Guest console uses the Cloud Hypervisor serial socket.

serial.sock

swiftctl connects using:

kubectl exec
socat

Example:

swiftctl console sample


SSH Access
SSH access is provided through cloud-init.
Seed profile injects:

authorized_keys

Once networking works:

ssh ubuntu@<primaryIP>


CLI
swiftctl is the KubeSwift CLI.
Planned commands:

swiftctl console
swiftctl start
swiftctl stop
swiftctl restart
swiftctl debug

Modeled after virtctl from KubeVirt.

Distribution
KubeSwift is distributed using OCI artifacts.
Images:

ghcr.io/projectbeskar/kubeswift/controller-manager
ghcr.io/projectbeskar/kubeswift/swiftletd

Helm chart:

oci://ghcr.io/projectbeskar/charts/kubeswift


Release Model

dev builds: sha-<git-sha>
RC builds:  vX.Y.Z-rc.N
stable:     vX.Y.Z


Smoke Test
Smoke test verifies full system functionality.
Steps:

create SwiftGuestClass
create SwiftImage
create SwiftSeedProfile
create SwiftGuest
wait for image ready
wait for guest running
verify seed mount
verify VM launch
verify networking

Success requires:

GuestRunning=True
status.network.primaryIP populated


Debugging Surfaces
Key debugging commands.
Inspect guest:

kubectl get swiftguest sample -o yaml

Launcher logs:

kubectl logs <pod> -c launcher

Runtime files:

kubectl exec -it <pod> -- ls /var/lib/kubeswift/run/<guest>

Console:

swiftctl console sample

Networking:

kubectl exec <pod> -- ip a
kubectl exec <pod> -- brctl show


Known Complexity Areas
These areas often cause bugs.
Networking

tap device reuse
bridge state
DHCP discovery

Image preparation

qcow2 → raw conversion
compressed qcow2 blocks

Status reporting

GuestRunning condition
IP discovery
controller status updates


Design Principles
KubeSwift prioritizes:

minimal architecture
clear runtime control
Cloud Hypervisor compatibility
Kubernetes-native APIs
strong operability

Avoid:

unnecessary dependencies
container-runtime abstractions
complex orchestration layers


Future Development Areas
Upcoming features include:

SSH access improvements
console reliability
guest lifecycle operations
networking robustness
status improvements

Long-term features may include:

snapshots
migration
advanced networking


Summary
KubeSwift is a lightweight Kubernetes-native VM runtime.
It combines:

Kubernetes controllers
Rust runtime
Cloud Hypervisor
cloud-init
OCI distribution

The goal is a simple, debuggable virtualization platform tightly integrated with Kubernetes.